id=04000US01&-geo_id=04000US02&-geo_id=04000US04&-geo_id=04000US05&-geo_id=04000US06&-geo_id=04000US08&-geo_id=04000US09&-geo_id=04000US10&-geo_id=04000US11&-geo_id=04000US12&-geo_id=04000US13&-geo_id=04000US15&-geo_id=04000US16&-geo_id=04000US17&-geo_id=04000US18&-geo_id=04000US19&-geo_id=04000US20&-geo_id=04000US21&-geo_id=04000US22&-geo_id=04000US23&-geo_id=04000US24&-geo_id=04000US25&-geo_id=04000US26&-geo_id=04000US27&-geo_id=04000US28&-geo_id=04000US29&-geo_id=04000US30&-geo_id=04000US31&-geo_id=04000US32&-geo_id=04000US33&-geo_id=04000US34&-geo_id=04000US35&-geo_id=04000US36&-geo_id=04000US37&-geo_id=04000US38&-geo_id=04000US39&-geo_id=04000US40&-geo_id=04000US41&-geo_id=04000US42&-geo_id=04000US44&-geo_id=04000US45&-geo_id=04000US46&-geo_id=04000US47&-geo_id=04000US48&-geo_id=04000US49&-geo_id=04000US50&-geo_id=04000US51&-geo_id=04000US53&-geo_id=04000US54&-geo_id=04000US55&-geo_id=04000US56&-geo_id=04000US72&-geo_id=31000US33100&-geo_id=31000US45300&-geo_id=33000US148&-geo_id=33000US176&-geo_id=33000US206&-geo_id=33000US288&-geo_id=33000US348&-geo_id=33000US408&-geo_id=33000US422&-geo_id=33000US428&-geo_id=33000US488&-geo_id=33000US548&-search_results=01000US&-parsed=true&-format=&-_lang=en|archive-date=10 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2012}}\n\n===German-American communities===\nToday, most German Americans have assimilated to the point they no longer have readily identifiable ethnic communities, though there are still many metropolitan areas where German is the most reported ethnicity, such as [[Cincinnati]], [[Northern Kentucky]], [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]], [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], [[Indianapolis]], [[Milwaukee]], [[Minneapolis \u2013 Saint Paul]], [[Pittsburgh]], and [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]].<ref name=\"Zeitlin\"/><ref>U.S. Census Bureau. [http://factfinder.census.gov/home/saff/main.html?_lang=en American FactFinder] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/68qlLjW1D?url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/legacy/aff_sunset.html?_lang=en |date=2012-07-02 }}</ref>\n\n====Communities with highest percentages of people of German ancestry====\nThe 25 U.S. communities with the highest percentage of residents claiming German ancestry are:<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.epodunk.com/ancestry/German.html |title=Ancestry Map of German Communities |publisher=Epodunk.com |accessdate=2008-08-12}}</ref>\n# [[Monterey Township, Putnam County, Ohio|Monterey, Ohio]] 83.6%\n# [[Granville Township, Mercer County, Ohio|Granville, Ohio]] 79.6%\n# [[St. Henry, Ohio]] 78.5%\n# [[Germantown Township, Clinton County, Illinois|Germantown Township, Illinois]] 77.6%\n# [[Jackson Township, Dubois County, Indiana|Jackson, Indiana]] 77.3%\n# [[Washington Township, Mercer County, Ohio|Washington, Ohio]] 77.2%\n# [[Saint Rose Township, Clinton County, Illinois|St. Rose, Illinois]] 77.1%\n# [[Butler Township, Mercer County, Ohio|Butler, Ohio]] 76.4%\n# [[Marion Township, Mercer County, Ohio|Marion, Ohio]] 76.3%\n# [[Jennings Township, Putnam County, Ohio|Jennings, Ohio]] and [[Germantown, Illinois|Germantown, Illinois (village)]] 75.6%\n# [[Coldwater, Ohio]] 74.9%\n# [[Jackson, Ohio]] 74.6%\n# [[Union, Ohio]] 74.1%\n# [[Minster, Ohio]] and [[Kalida, Ohio]] 73.5%\n# [[Greensburg Township, Putnam County, Ohio|Greensburg, Ohio]] 73.4%\n# [[Aviston, Illinois]] 72.5%\n# [[Teutopolis, IL|Teutopolis, Illinois (village)]] 72.4%\n# [[Teutopolis Township, Effingham County, Illinois|Teutopolis, Illinois (township)]] and [[Cottonwood Township, Brown County, Minnesota|Cottonwood, Minnesota]] 72.3%\n# [[Dallas Township, Michigan|Dallas, Michigan]] 71.7%\n# [[Gibson Township, Mercer County, Ohio|Gibson, Ohio]] 71.6%\n# [[Marshfield, Fond du Lac County, Wisconsin|Town of Marshfield, Fond du Lac County, Wisconsin]] 71.5%\n# [[Santa Fe Township, Clinton County, Illinois|Santa Fe, Illinois]] 70.8%\n# [[Recovery Township, Mercer County, Ohio|Recovery, Ohio]] 70.4%\n# [[Brothertown, Wisconsin|Town of Brotherto