eene (eds.), ''Perspectives on Milwaukee's Past''. Champaign: University of Illinois Press, 2009.\n* Miller, Zane L. \"Cincinnati Germans and the Invention of an Ethnic Group\", ''Queen City Heritage: The Journal of the Cincinnati Historical Society'' 42 (Fall 1984): 13\u201322.\n* {{cite book|author=Parish, Peter J., ed. |title=Reader's Guide to American History|year=2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=294\u201395}}\n\n===Primary sources===\n* Kamphoefner, Walter D., and Wolfgang Helbich, eds. ''Germans in the Civil War; The Letters They Wrote Home''. (U of North Carolina Press, 2006).\n* Kamphoefner, Walter D., Wolfgang Johannes Helbich and Ulrike Sommer, eds. ''News from the Land of Freedom: German Immigrants Write Home''. (Cornell University Press, 1991).\n* {{cite web |url= http://flps.newberry.org/#filters/group/german?page=1|title=German |work=Chicago Foreign Language Press Survey |year=1942 |publisher=Chicago Public Library Omnibus Project of the [[Works Progress Administration]] of Illinois |via=[[Newberry Library]] }} (English translations of selected German-language newspaper articles, 1855-1938).\n\n===In German===\n* Emmerich, Alexander. ''Geschichte der Deutschen in Amerika von 1680 bis in die Gegenwart''. (2013).\n* Rehs, Michael. ''Wurzeln in fremder Erde: Zur Geschichte der s\u00fcdwestdeutschen Auswanderung nach Amerika'' DRW-Verlag, 1984. {{ISBN|3-87181-231-5}}\n* {{Citation |title = American Newspaper Directory |date =1880 |location = New York |publisher = [[George P. Rowell|Geo. P. Rowell & Co.]] |chapterurl= https://archive.org/stream/geoprowellcosame1880newy#page/517/mode/1up |chapter= List of Newspapers and Periodicals Printed Wholly or in Part in Languages Other Than English: German }}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|German diaspora in the United States}}\n\n===German-American history and culture===\n* [https://www.loc.gov/rr/european/imde/germchro.html Chronology: Germans in America]\n* [http://maxkade.iupui.edu/merrill/home.html German Immigrant Culture in America: Syllabus (1998)]\n* [http://www.auswandererbriefe.de Emigrant Letters to Germany (in German)]\n* [https://www.immigrantentrepreneurship.org/entries.php German-American Business Biographies] from the [[German Historical Institute]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090529145701/http://www.gamhof.org/famous_ga.html German-American Hall of Fame]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181113073213/https://mki.wisc.edu/sites/mki.wisc.edu/files/HGIA_booklet.pdf How German Is American?]\n* [http://www.germanhollywood.com/ The German-Hollywood Connection]\n* [http://flps.newberry.org/ Chicago Foreign Language Press Survey: English translations of 120,000 pages of newspaper articles from Chicago's foreign language press from 1855 to 1938, many from German papers.]\n\n===German-American organizations===\n* [https://gahmusa.org/ German-American Heritage Museum of the USA]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181228070758/http://steubensociety.org/ Steuben Society of America]\n* [http://www.gahc.org/ German American Heritage Center]\n* [http://www.grhs.org/ Germans from Russia Heritage Society]\n* [https://mki.wisc.edu/ Max Kade Institute for German-American Studies] at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n* [http://maxkade.iupui.edu Max Kade German-American Center] at [[Indiana University \u2013 Purdue University Indianapolis]]\n* [http://www.germantownhistory.org/ The Germantown Historical Society (Philadelphia)]\n* [http://www.germansociety.org The German Society of Pennsylvania (oldest German Society in the U.S.)]\n* [http://www.pgs.org/default.asp The Pennsylvania German Society]\n* [https://www.kutztown.edu/about-ku/administrative-offices/pennsylvania-german-cultural-heritage-center.htm Pennsylvania German Cultural Heritage Center] at [[Kutztown University]]\n* [http://www.ighs.org Indiana German Heritage Society]\n\n===Local German-American history and culture===\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/6PJL8tGZt?url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/512.html Germans in Chicago]\n* [http://www.germantracesnyc.org German Traces NYC from the Goethe-Institut]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070820091545/http://www.washjeff.edu/german/pittsburgh/ Interactive German-History Map of Pittsburgh]\n* [http://www.oktoberfestzinzinnati.com/okt.aspx?menu_id=256&id=8478 Zinzinnati History (Cincinnati, Ohio)]\n* [http://www.stimmungstunde.com Milwaukee German-American Radio Program]\n* [http://pghmannerchor.com Teutonia M\u00e4nnerchor in Pittsburgh]\n* [https://mki.wisc.edu/sites/mki.wisc.edu/files/graphics/Some_German_Contributions_to_Wisconsin_Life-Seifert.pdf Some German Contributions to Wisconsin Life]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles and topics related to German American\n|state=collapsed\n|list1=\n{{German Americans by location}}\n{{European Americans}}\n{{Demographics of the United States}}\n{{German diaspora}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American people of German descent| ]]\n[[Category:German American| ]]\n[[Category:German diaspora by country|American]]\n[[Category:European-American society]]\n", "name_user": "Whyamidoingthisidk", "label": "safe", "comment": "this only changed a few words and this clearly explains more of the germans", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_Americans"}
{"title_page": "Rose Leiman Goldemberg", "text_new": "{{Other people|Rose Leiman Goldemberg}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Rose Leiman Goldemberg\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1928|05|17}}\n| birth_place      = [[Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation       = [[Playwright]], [[screenwriter]], [[author]], [[poet]]\n| awards           = [[Writers Guild of America Award]]<ref name=\"nypl-burning\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321#c1350351|title=NY Public Library Archives - Burning Bed}}</ref>, 2 [[Emmy Award]] Nominations<ref name=\"nypl-burning\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/rose-leiman-goldemberg|title=Emmys Official Website}}</ref>, [[Humanitas Prize]] Nomination<ref name=\"nypl-burning\" /> <ref name=\"dps-bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dramatists.com/dps/bios.aspx?authorbio=Rose+Leiman+Goldemberg|title=Dramatists Play Service Official Website}}</ref>, [[American Women in Radio and Television]] Award<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />, Humanitarian Award for Drama<ref name=\"dps-bio\" /> <ref name=\"playbill\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/picon-pie-serves-its-last-slice-of-yiddish-theatre-lore-june-2-in-nyc-but-a-tour-is-cooking-com-126013|title=Playbill.com}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Rose Leiman Goldemberg''' (born May 17, 1928) is an American [[playwright]], [[screenwriter]], [[poet]], and [[author]] of fiction and non-fiction books and stories.\n\nGoldemberg is known for her dramatic and musical works based on biographies and true stories. Her earliest writings were poetry and she has written professionally for radio, television, film, and the stage. The lives of both ordinary and famous women, feminism, and Jewish culture are frequent themes in her writing.\n\nRose Leiman Goldemberg's most celebrated play is the internationally acclaimed, ''Letters Home'' about the life of Sylvia Plath and her mother. It has been translated into numerous languages and been honored all over the world.<ref name=\"dps-bio\" /> Like ''Letters Home'', Goldemberg's plays frequently incorporate biographical material, as with ''Sophie'' (1987), about entertainer [[Sophie Tucker]]; and ''[[Picon Pie]]'' (2004), about Yiddish theater actress [[Molly Picon]]. Her plays have been produced widely [[Off-Broadway]], in venues throughout the United States, and internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321#bioghist|title=New York Public Library Archives}}</ref>\n\nGoldemberg's most prominent work on TV was ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' (1984), a television movie based on the true story of a survivor of domestic violence, played by [[Farrah Fawcett]]. Another well-known television movie written by Goldemberg, ''[[Stone Pillow]]'' (1985), starred [[Lucille Ball]] as a homeless woman. Other screenplays written by Goldemberg include ''Land of Hope'' (1976), and ''[[Mother and Daughter: The Loving War]]'' (1980). Goldemberg was more involved with the production and filming of television movies, mini-series, and shows than is typical for screenwriters, making cast recommendations and visiting the sets. Most of her screenplays are dramas.\n\nGoldemberg has also taught the subjects of English and Theater at The City College of New York and Fairleigh Dickinson University. She is a published author of such books as ''Adios, Hollywood'' and ''Antique Jewelry: A Practical & Passionate Guide.'' She is also an award-winning poet and author of short stories.<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />\n\n==Early years==\nRose Leiman Goldemberg was born in 1928 in the [[Port Richmond]] neighborhood of [[Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. She started writing at the age of five, and entered [[Brooklyn College]] in 1944 at the age of 16. After receiving her BA (magna cum laude) from Brooklyn College, she attended [[Ohio State University]] on a teaching assistantship and received her MA.<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\">{{cite thesis|last=O'rourke|first=Joyce Williams|date=1988|title=New Female Playwrights in the American Theatre, 1973-1983: a Critical Analysis of Thought in Selected Plays.|publisher=LSU Historical Dissertations and Theses|url=http://digitalcommons.lsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=5524&context=gradschool_disstheses}}</ref> Upon graduating she started working at the newly formed [[TV Guide Magazine]], where she reviewed TV scripts and wrote plot summaries. It was there that she decided to become a screenwriter. She studied at the [[American Theatre Wing]] and [[Columbia University]]<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />, and has studied under [[Lee Strasberg]] and Ira Cirker. She began her screenwriting career by writing religious TV scripts for Pamela Ilott at CBS.\n\n==Career==\nGoldemberg's ''Gandhiji'' was chosen for the O'Neill Conference in 1970. At the time she was a mother and a full-time teacher, along with being a playwright.<ref name=\"nytimes09-1970\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/09/20/archives/woman-writer-mans-world-woman-playwright-mans-world.html|title=New York Times Archives Sept. 20, 1970}}</ref> ''Gandhiji'' premiered in 1977 at Back Alley's downtown studio, 617 F St. NW, Washington D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1977/05/10/gandhiji-a-westerners-point-of-view/dcb6985a-a5d5-40f0-9bbd-7ac6a90cc7f6/|title=Washington Post Archives May 10, 1977}}</ref> It garnered a Robby Award<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />, and helped to establish Goldemberg as a dramatist.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sweet |first=Jeffrey |title=The O'Neill: The Transformation of Modern American Theater |publisher=Yale University Press |date=2014 |page=124 |isbn=9780300206937 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=NFHwAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA124}}</ref> ''Gandhiji'' was also honored in Burns Mantle's \"Best Plays of 1982-1983.\"<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />\n\n''Land of Hope'' was a pilot for a television series written by Goldemberg, which aired on the [[CBS]] network in 1976. It was about the immigrant experience in the United States. ''Land of Hope'' was Goldemberg's break into the television industry.<ref name=\"NYWIF interview\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wUgAlku3Og|title=NY Women in Film and Television Interview}}</ref>\n\nGoldemberg's play ''Letters Home'' premiered as part of The Women's Project at [[The American Place Theatre]] in New York City in 1979. It dramatizes the correspondence between author [[Sylvia Plath]] and her mother. It was later staged at the Theatre at New End in London; Playbox Theatre in Melbourne; and in Paris; Copenhagen; Montreal; Tel Aviv; Los Angeles; and other cities. In 1986, French feminist film director [[Chantal Akerman]] directed it for film.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321#detailed|title=New York Public Library Archives - Detailed Description}}</ref>\n\nGoldemberg's ''Mother and Daughter: The Loving War'' was a TV movie first broadcast on the CBS network in 1980, which was nominated for a Writers Guild of America Best Drama Award.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n\nGoldemberg's television movie ''Born Beautiful'' was broadcast on the [[NBC]] network in 1982. The work took a critical view of the modeling industry.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />\n\nGoldemberg wrote the screenplay and co-produced the television film ''[[The Burning Bed]]'', which was originally broadcast by the [[NBC]] network in 1984. It was based on the true story of [[Francine Hughes]], played by [[Farrah Fawcett]], a victim of domestic violence who killed her abuser by setting their bed on fire. The movie earned very high ratings, was rebroadcast many times, and sparked public discourse about domestic violence. The screenplay won the [[Writers Guild of America Award]] for Best Dramatic Adaptation, and was nominated for [[Emmy]] and Humanitas Awards.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />\n\n''[[Stone Pillow]]'' was a television movie written by Goldemberg, which originally aired on the [[CBS]] network in 1985. It starred [[Lucille Ball]] in the dramatic role of a homeless woman living on the streets of New York City.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> ''Stone Pillow'' ranked as one of the top 10 highest rated telecasts the week that it aired.<ref>https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1985/BC-1985-11-18.pdf</ref>\n\n''Death at Dinner'', a comedy, which aired on the [[PBS]] network in 1985, was a segment of The Booth television series written by Goldemberg.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n\nGoldemberg's ''Sophie'', a musical about the life of American singer and actress [[Sophie Tucker]], was first staged at the Jewish Repertory Theater, starring Judith Cohen, in 1987.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />\n\nGoldemberg wrote the television movie ''Dark Holiday'', which aired on the [[NBC]] network in 1989. It tells the true story of an American woman kidnapped in Turkey.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />  \n\nGoldemberg\u2019s musical ''[[Picon Pie]]'' opened in Santa Monica, CA at The Santa Monica Playhouse April 6, 2002<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2002/legit/reviews/picon-pie-1200550155/|title=Variety.com review}}</ref> and starred Barbara Minkus as [[Molly Picon]].  The production toured throughout the country, appearing Off-Broadway at the [[DR2 Theater]] on July 15, 2005 in New York City, moving to the [[Lamb's Theatre]] on February 17, 2005. It closed on June 2, 2005.<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7mqtcFDkW2kC&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=picon+pie+2005#v=onepage&q=picon%20pie%202005&f=false | title = Theatre World | isbn = 978-1-55783-703-5 | last1 = Willis | first1 = John A | last2 = Hodges | first2 = Ben | date = March 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Rose Leiman Goldemberg was interviewed by NY Women in Film and Television. In the interview Goldemberg talks about how she broke into television and shares stories about the experiences she had while working in the industry. <ref name=\"NYWIF interview\" />\n\nGoldemberg's work has been archived in the [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]] at Lincoln Center, which houses one of the world's largest collections of materials relating to the performing arts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321|title=NY Public Library for the Performing Arts}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nRose married Raymond Schiller in 1945 and had two children, a son in 1960 and a daughter in 1964. She and Raymond Schiller were divorced in 1968. Rose married Robert Goldemberg in 1969. They divorced in 1989.\n\n==Work==\n;Screenwriting\n* ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' (Tisch-Avnet, NBC) Co-producer ++<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''The Desiray Bartak Story'' (Arnold Shapiro Prod., CBS) \n* ''The Rainbow Warrior'' (TNT, RG and Partner) Co-producer \n* ''A Velvet Glove'' (Dave Bell Productions, ABC)\n* ''Unnatural Acts'' (HBO New York)\n* ''Dark Holiday'' (Orion, NBC)<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''Fight for Freedom'' (Readers Digest Ent., CBS) \n* ''[[Stone Pillow]]'' (Schaefer/Karpf Prod., CBS) +<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''Florence Nightingale'' (3 hrs.) (Gerald Abrams, ABC) + \n* ''Out of Wedlock'' (Readers Digest Ent., ABC)\n* ''Death at Dinner'' (Schaefer/Karpf Prod., PBS)<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''Victory of the Heart'' (Valerie Harper, TAL Prod, MGM, ABC)<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}} \n* ''Born Beautiful'' (Telecom Entertainment, NBC) +<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''The Jonas Salk Story'' (Robert Fuisz, Ent. Partners, NBC) \n* ''Memoirs of an Ex-Prom Queen'' (Lorimar, CBS) \n* ''Mother and Daughter, the Loving War'' (Edgar Scherick, ABC) +<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''A Celebration of Women'' (Robert Fuisz, Ent. Partners,CBS) \n* ''Land of Hope'' (Herb Brodkin, CBS) series pilot<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''[[Growing Pains]]'' (David Susskind, CBS) series pilot<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}} \n* ''Life in the Fast Lane'' (Nancy Malone, CBS) series pilot\n* ''The Medicine Men'' (Herb Brodkin, Titus Prod, NBC) pilot<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n+ denotes award nomination, ++ denotes first-place award\n\n;Plays\n* ''[[Picon Pie]]'' (musical, off Broadway, Fla, touring) ++\n* ''Adios, Hollywood'' (musical, book and lyrics) John Harms Center for the Arts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.debrabarsha.com/MUSICALS.html|title=Barsha Adios}}</ref>\n* ''Sophie'' (musical, book and lyrics), Jewish Rep, NY<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Letters Home'' - premiered AMERICAN PLACE THEATER, NY, then London, Melbourne, Paris (with Delphine Seyrig), French tour Sweden, Norway, Holland, Poland, Scotland, tours of Scotland and Wales, Copenhagen, Istanbul, Capetown, Budapest, Montreal, Toronto, Tel Aviv, Edinburgh Festival, Dublin Festival -- and in U.S.: San Diego, Los Angeles, many tours and anthologies; Publ. Samuel French. ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Apples in Eden'' (musical book and lyrics) Kent, Ohio. ++ <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|260}}\n* ''Love One Another'' - New Dramatists, NYC.<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''The Rabinowitz Gambit'' - Cleveland Playhouse, 18th Street Playhouse. NYC, Whole Theater Company of Montclair, N.J. ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''The Merry War'', New Dramatists, toured US. +<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Gandhiji'' - LA Actors Theater; Back Alley, Washington, D C ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Rites of Passage'' - Astor Place Theater. NYC, FDU Theater, NJ. ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Marching as to War'' \u2013 US tours, published by Dramatists Play Service<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|53}}\n+ denotes award nomination, ++ denotes first-place award\n\n;Books, Articles, Short Stories \n* ''The Way It Happened'' (novel, current)\n* ''Antique Jewelry: A Practical and Passionate Guide' (Crown) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''All About Jewelry'' (Arbor House) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''The Complete Book of Natural Cosmetics'' (Simon & Schuster) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''Here's Egg on Your Face'' (Hewitt House, Pocket Books) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* New York Times Arts Section: ''Woman Playwright, Man's World''<ref name=\"nytimes09-1970\" />\n\n==Awards and Honors==\n* ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' - [[Writers Guild of America Award]], Best Dramatic Adaptation; [[Emmy]] Nomination, Outstanding writing; [[American Women in Radio and Television]] Award; Humanitarian Award for Drama, L.A. Commission on Assaults Against Women; honored by [[The American Film Institute]], as part of the Permanent collection.<ref name=\"nypl-burning\" />\n* ''[[Stone Pillow]]'' - Religion in Media Award, Best TV Drama.<ref name=\"latimes-stone\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-02-22-me-10615-story.html|title=LA Times - Stone Pillow}}</ref>\n* [[Humanitas Prize]] Nominations: ''[[Stone Pillow]]'', ''[[The Burning Bed]]'', ''Born Beautiful'', ''Mother and Daughter: The Loving War'', ''Land of Hope''.<ref name=\"playbill\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/picon-pie-serves-its-last-slice-of-yiddish-theatre-lore-june-2-in-nyc-but-a-tour-is-cooking-com-126013|title=Playbill.com}}</ref> <ref name=\"nypl-burning\" />\n* National Library of Poetry - Editors' Choice, Outstanding Achievement in Poetry\n* Story Magazine Award - Famous Fiction Competition \n* ''Mother and Daughter: The Loving War'' - [[Writers Guild of America]] Best Drama Nomination; [[American Women in Radio and Television]] Award.<ref name=\"playbill\" />\n* ''Letters Home'' - Best Play of The Year, L. A. Times, awards at many international festivals.\n* ''[[Picon Pie]]'' \u2014 L.A. [[Ovation award]] nomination, best new musical\n* ''Gandhiji'' - [[L.A. Times]] Award, chosen for O'Neill Conference<ref name=\"nytimes09-1970\" />; in Burns Mantle's Best Plays of 1982-1983\n* ''The Rabinowitz Gambit'' - 1st Prize, Sullivan County Drama Award<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''The Merry War'' - NJ State Council on the Arts Grant<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]] Grant for Women in Theater\n* ''Voices in My Head'' - Earplay Purchase Award, [[Edwin Howard Armstrong Award]] for Best Radio Drama<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://svn.lib.umd.edu/fedora/tags/archivesum.pre-fedora/html/MdU.ead.npba.0031.html|title=University of Maryland}}</ref>\n* [[American Theater Wing]] Playwriting Scholarship Award\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.roseleimangoldemberg.com/biography.htm Rose Leiman Goldemberg's Official Website]\n* {{IMDb name|0325380}}\n* [https://directories.wga.org/member/86c29d1f-9e58-4295-aae3-eaeaf7c7c8b6 WGA Writer Page]\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321 NY Public Library - Rose Leiman Goldemberg papers\n1968-2014]\n<!--- Categories --->\n\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:TV Guide]]\n[[Category:CBS people]]\n[[Category:National Broadcasting Company]]\n[[Category:Fairleigh Dickinson University faculty]]\n[[Category:City College of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Rose Leiman Goldemberg}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Rose Leiman Goldemberg\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1928|05|17}}\n| birth_place      = [[Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation       = [[Playwright]], [[screenwriter]], [[author]], [[poet]]\n| awards           = [[Writers Guild of America Award]]<ref name=\"nypl-burning\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321#c1350351|title=NY Public Library Archives - Burning Bed}}</ref>, 2 [[Emmy Award]] Nominations<ref name=\"nypl-burning\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/rose-leiman-goldemberg|title=Emmys Official Website}}</ref>, [[Humanitas Prize]] Nomination<ref name=\"nypl-burning\" /> <ref name=\"dps-bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dramatists.com/dps/bios.aspx?authorbio=Rose+Leiman+Goldemberg|title=Dramatists Play Service Official Website}}</ref>, [[American Women in Radio and Television]] Award<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />, Humanitarian Award for Drama<ref name=\"dps-bio\" /> <ref name=\"playbill\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/picon-pie-serves-its-last-slice-of-yiddish-theatre-lore-june-2-in-nyc-but-a-tour-is-cooking-com-126013|title=Playbill.com}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Rose Leiman Goldemberg''' (born May 17, 1928) is an American [[playwright]], [[screenwriter]], [[poet]], and [[author]] of fiction and non-fiction books and stories.\n\nGoldemberg is known for her dramatic and musical works based on biographies and true stories. Her earliest writings were poetry and she has written professionally for radio, television, film, and the stage. The lives of both ordinary and famous women, feminism, and Jewish culture are frequent themes in her writing.\n\nRose Leiman Goldemberg's most celebrated play is the internationally acclaimed, ''Letters Home'' about the life of Sylvia Plath and her mother. It has been translated into numerous languages and been honored all over the world.<ref name=\"dps-bio\" /> Like ''Letters Home'', Goldemberg's plays frequently incorporate biographical material, as with ''Sophie'' (1987), about entertainer [[Sophie Tucker]]; and ''[[Picon Pie]]'' (2004), about Yiddish theater actress [[Molly Picon]]. Her plays have been produced widely [[Off-Broadway]], in venues throughout the United States, and internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321#bioghist|title=New York Public Library Archives}}</ref>\n\nGoldemberg's most prominent work on TV was ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' (1984), a television movie based on the true story of a survivor of domestic violence, played by [[Farrah Fawcett]]. Another well-known television movie written by Goldemberg, ''[[Stone Pillow]]'' (1985), starred [[Lucille Ball]] as a homeless woman. Other screenplays written by Goldemberg include ''Land of Hope'' (1976), and ''[[Mother and Daughter: The Loving War]]'' (1980). Goldemberg was more involved with the production and filming of television movies, mini-series, and shows than is typical for screenwriters, making cast recommendations and visiting the sets. Most of her screenplays are dramas.\n\nGoldemberg has also taught the subjects of English and Theater at The City College of New York and Fairleigh Dickinson University. She is a published author of such books as ''Adios, Hollywood'' and ''Antique Jewelry: A Practical & Passionate Guide.'' She is also an award-winning poet and author of short stories.<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />\n\n==Early years==\nRose Leiman Goldemberg was born in 1928 in the [[Port Richmond]] neighborhood of [[Staten Island]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. She started writing at the age of five, and entered [[Brooklyn College]] in 1944 at the age of 16. After receiving her BA (magna cum laude) from Brooklyn College, she attended [[Ohio State University]] on a teaching assistantship and received her MA.<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\">{{cite thesis|last=O'rourke|first=Joyce Williams|date=1988|title=New Female Playwrights in the American Theatre, 1973-1983: a Critical Analysis of Thought in Selected Plays.|publisher=LSU Historical Dissertations and Theses|url=http://digitalcommons.lsu.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=5524&context=gradschool_disstheses}}</ref> Upon graduating she started working at the newly formed [[TV Guide Magazine]], where she reviewed TV scripts and wrote plot summaries. It was there that she decided to become a screenwriter. She studied at the [[American Theatre Wing]] and [[Columbia University]]<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />, and has studied under [[Lee Strasberg]] and Ira Cirker. She began her screenwriting career by writing religious TV scripts for Pamela Ilott at CBS.\n\n==Career==\nGoldemberg's ''Gandhiji'' was chosen for the O'Neill Conference in 1970. At the time she was a mother and a full-time teacher, along with being a playwright.<ref name=\"nytimes09-1970\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/09/20/archives/woman-writer-mans-world-woman-playwright-mans-world.html|title=New York Times Archives Sept. 20, 1970}}</ref> ''Gandhiji'' premiered in 1977 at Back Alley's downtown studio, 617 F St. NW, Washington D.C.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1977/05/10/gandhiji-a-westerners-point-of-view/dcb6985a-a5d5-40f0-9bbd-7ac6a90cc7f6/|title=Washington Post Archives May 10, 1977}}</ref> It garnered a Robby Award<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />, and helped to establish Goldemberg as a dramatist.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sweet |first=Jeffrey |title=The O'Neill: The Transformation of Modern American Theater |publisher=Yale University Press |date=2014 |page=124 |isbn=9780300206937 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=NFHwAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA124}}</ref> ''Gandhiji'' was also honored in Burns Mantle's \"Best Plays of 1982-1983.\"<ref name=\"dps-bio\" />\n\n''Land of Hope'' was a pilot for a television series written by Goldemberg, which aired on the [[CBS]] network in 1976. It was about the immigrant experience in the United States. ''Land of Hope'' was Goldemberg's break into the television industry.<ref name=\"NYWIF interview\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4wUgAlku3Og|title=NY Women in Film and Television Interview}}</ref>\n\nGoldemberg's play ''Letters Home'' premiered as part of The Women's Project at [[The American Place Theatre]] in New York City in 1979. It dramatizes the correspondence between author [[Sylvia Plath]] and her mother. It was later staged at the Theatre at New End in London; Playbox Theatre in Melbourne; and in Paris; Copenhagen; Montreal; Tel Aviv; Los Angeles; and other cities. In 1986, French feminist film director [[Chantal Akerman]] directed it for film.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\">{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321#detailed|title=New York Public Library Archives - Detailed Description}}</ref>\n\nGoldemberg's ''Mother and Daughter: The Loving War'' was a TV movie first broadcast on the CBS network in 1980, which was nominated for a Writers Guild of America Best Drama Award.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n\nGoldemberg's television movie ''Born Beautiful'' was broadcast on the [[NBC]] network in 1982. The work took a critical view of the modeling industry.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />\n\nGoldemberg wrote the screenplay and co-produced the television film ''[[The Burning Bed]]'', which was originally broadcast by the [[NBC]] network in 1984. It was based on the true story of [[Francine Hughes]], played by [[Farrah Fawcett]], a victim of domestic violence who killed her abuser by setting their bed on fire. The movie earned very high ratings, was rebroadcast many times, and sparked public discourse about domestic violence. The screenplay won the [[Writers Guild of America Award]] for Best Dramatic Adaptation, and was nominated for [[Emmy]] and Humanitas Awards.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />\n\n''[[Stone Pillow]]'' was a television movie written by Goldemberg, which originally aired on the [[CBS]] network in 1985. It starred [[Lucille Ball]] in the dramatic role of a homeless woman living on the streets of New York City.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> ''Stone Pillow'' ranked as one of the top 10 highest rated telecasts the week that it aired.<ref>https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC/BC-1985/BC-1985-11-18.pdf</ref>\n\n''Death at Dinner'', a comedy, which aired on the [[PBS]] network in 1985, was a segment of The Booth television series written by Goldemberg.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n\nGoldemberg's ''Sophie'', a musical about the life of American singer and actress [[Sophie Tucker]], was first staged at the Jewish Repertory Theater, starring Judith Cohen, in 1987.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />\n\nGoldemberg wrote the television movie ''Dark Holiday'', which aired on the [[NBC]] network in 1989. It tells the true story of an American woman kidnapped in Turkey.<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" />  \n\nGoldemberg\u2019s musical ''[[Picon Pie]]'' opened in Santa Monica, CA at The Santa Monica Playhouse April 6, 2002<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2002/legit/reviews/picon-pie-1200550155/|title=Variety.com review}}</ref> and starred Barbara Minkus as [[Molly Picon]].  The production toured throughout the country, appearing Off-Broadway at the [[DR2 Theater]] on July 15, 2005 in New York City, moving to the [[Lamb's Theatre]] on February 17, 2005. It closed on June 2, 2005.<ref>{{Cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7mqtcFDkW2kC&pg=PA140&lpg=PA140&dq=picon+pie+2005#v=onepage&q=picon%20pie%202005&f=false | title = Theatre World | isbn = 978-1-55783-703-5 | last1 = Willis | first1 = John A | last2 = Hodges | first2 = Ben | date = March 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Rose Leiman Goldemberg was inteviewed by NY Women in Film and Television. In the interview Goldemberg talks about how she broke into television and shares stories about the experiences she had while working in the industry. <ref name=\"NYWIF interview\" />\n\nGoldemberg's work has been archived in the [[New York Public Library for the Performing Arts]] at Lincoln Center, which houses one of the world's largest collections of materials relating to the performing arts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321|title=NY Public Library for the Performing Arts}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nRose married Raymond Schiller in 1945 and had two children, a son in 1960 and a daughter in 1964. She and Raymond Schiller were divorced in 1968. Rose married Robert Goldemberg in 1969. They divorced in 1989.\n\n==Work==\n;Screenwriting\n* ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' (Tisch-Avnet, NBC) Co-producer ++<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''The Desiray Bartak Story'' (Arnold Shapiro Prod., CBS) \n* ''The Rainbow Warrior'' (TNT, RG and Partner) Co-producer \n* ''A Velvet Glove'' (Dave Bell Productions, ABC)\n* ''Unnatural Acts'' (HBO New York)\n* ''Dark Holiday'' (Orion, NBC)<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''Fight for Freedom'' (Readers Digest Ent., CBS) \n* ''[[Stone Pillow]]'' (Schaefer/Karpf Prod., CBS) +<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''Florence Nightingale'' (3 hrs.) (Gerald Abrams, ABC) + \n* ''Out of Wedlock'' (Readers Digest Ent., ABC)\n* ''Death at Dinner'' (Schaefer/Karpf Prod., PBS)<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''Victory of the Heart'' (Valerie Harper, TAL Prod, MGM, ABC)<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}} \n* ''Born Beautiful'' (Telecom Entertainment, NBC) +<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''The Jonas Salk Story'' (Robert Fuisz, Ent. Partners, NBC) \n* ''Memoirs of an Ex-Prom Queen'' (Lorimar, CBS) \n* ''Mother and Daughter, the Loving War'' (Edgar Scherick, ABC) +<ref name=\"nypl-bio_detailed\" /> \n* ''A Celebration of Women'' (Robert Fuisz, Ent. Partners,CBS) \n* ''Land of Hope'' (Herb Brodkin, CBS) series pilot<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''[[Growing Pains]]'' (David Susskind, CBS) series pilot<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}} \n* ''Life in the Fast Lane'' (Nancy Malone, CBS) series pilot\n* ''The Medicine Men'' (Herb Brodkin, Titus Prod, NBC) pilot<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n+ denotes award nomination, ++ denotes first-place award\n\n;Plays\n* ''[[Picon Pie]]'' (musical, off Broadway, Fla, touring) ++\n* ''Adios, Hollywood'' (musical, book and lyrics) John Harms Center for the Arts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.debrabarsha.com/MUSICALS.html|title=Barsha Adios}}</ref>\n* ''Sophie'' (musical, book and lyrics), Jewish Rep, NY<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Letters Home'' - premiered AMERICAN PLACE THEATER, NY, then London, Melbourne, Paris (with Delphine Seyrig), French tour Sweden, Norway, Holland, Poland, Scotland, tours of Scotland and Wales, Copenhagen, Istanbul, Capetown, Budapest, Montreal, Toronto, Tel Aviv, Edinburgh Festival, Dublin Festival -- and in U.S.: San Diego, Los Angeles, many tours and anthologies; Publ. Samuel French. ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Apples in Eden'' (musical book and lyrics) Kent, Ohio. ++ <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|260}}\n* ''Love One Another'' - New Dramatists, NYC.<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''The Rabinowitz Gambit'' - Cleveland Playhouse, 18th Street Playhouse. NYC, Whole Theater Company of Montclair, N.J. ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''The Merry War'', New Dramatists, toured US. +<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Gandhiji'' - LA Actors Theater; Back Alley, Washington, D C ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Rites of Passage'' - Astor Place Theater. NYC, FDU Theater, NJ. ++<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''Marching as to War'' \u2013 US tours, published by Dramatists Play Service<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|53}}\n+ denotes award nomination, ++ denotes first-place award\n\n;Books, Articles, Short Stories \n* ''The Way It Happened'' (novel, current)\n* ''Antique Jewelry: A Practical and Passionate Guide' (Crown) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''All About Jewelry'' (Arbor House) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''The Complete Book of Natural Cosmetics'' (Simon & Schuster) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* ''Here's Egg on Your Face'' (Hewitt House, Pocket Books) <ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* New York Times Arts Section: ''Woman Playwright, Man's World''<ref name=\"nytimes09-1970\" />\n\n==Awards and Honors==\n* ''[[The Burning Bed]]'' - [[Writers Guild of America Award]], Best Dramatic Adaptation; [[Emmy]] Nomination, Outstanding writing; [[American Women in Radio and Television]] Award; Humanitarian Award for Drama, L.A. Commission on Assaults Against Women; honored by [[The American Film Institute]], as part of the Permanent collection.<ref name=\"nypl-burning\" />\n* ''[[Stone Pillow]]'' - Religion in Media Award, Best TV Drama.<ref name=\"latimes-stone\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1986-02-22-me-10615-story.html|title=LA Times - Stone Pillow}}</ref>\n* [[Humanitas Prize]] Nominations: ''[[Stone Pillow]]'', ''[[The Burning Bed]]'', ''Born Beautiful'', ''Mother and Daughter: The Loving War'', ''Land of Hope''.<ref name=\"playbill\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/picon-pie-serves-its-last-slice-of-yiddish-theatre-lore-june-2-in-nyc-but-a-tour-is-cooking-com-126013|title=Playbill.com}}</ref> <ref name=\"nypl-burning\" />\n* National Library of Poetry - Editors' Choice, Outstanding Achievement in Poetry\n* Story Magazine Award - Famous Fiction Competition \n* ''Mother and Daughter: The Loving War'' - [[Writers Guild of America]] Best Drama Nomination; [[American Women in Radio and Television]] Award.<ref name=\"playbill\" />\n* ''Letters Home'' - Best Play of The Year, L. A. Times, awards at many international festivals.\n* ''[[Picon Pie]]'' \u2014 L.A. [[Ovation award]] nomination, best new musical\n* ''Gandhiji'' - [[L.A. Times]] Award, chosen for O'Neill Conference<ref name=\"nytimes09-1970\" />; in Burns Mantle's Best Plays of 1982-1983\n* ''The Rabinowitz Gambit'' - 1st Prize, Sullivan County Drama Award<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|52}}\n* ''The Merry War'' - NJ State Council on the Arts Grant<ref name=\"LSU Thesis\" />{{rp|51}}\n* [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]] Grant for Women in Theater\n* ''Voices in My Head'' - Earplay Purchase Award, [[Edwin Howard Armstrong Award]] for Best Radio Drama<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://svn.lib.umd.edu/fedora/tags/archivesum.pre-fedora/html/MdU.ead.npba.0031.html|title=University of Maryland}}</ref>\n* [[American Theater Wing]] Playwriting Scholarship Award\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.roseleimangoldemberg.com/biography.htm Rose Leiman Goldemberg's Official Website]\n* {{IMDb name|0325380}}\n* [https://directories.wga.org/member/86c29d1f-9e58-4295-aae3-eaeaf7c7c8b6 WGA Writer Page]\n* [http://archives.nypl.org/the/23321 NY Public Library - Rose Leiman Goldemberg papers\n1968-2014]\n<!--- Categories --->\n\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:TV Guide]]\n[[Category:CBS people]]\n[[Category:National Broadcasting Company]]\n[[Category:Fairleigh Dickinson University faculty]]\n[[Category:City College of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "inteviewed->interviewed -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rose_Leiman_Goldemberg"}
{"title_page": "Nuwan Pradeep", "text_new": "{{short description|Sri Lankan cricketer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Nuwan Pradeep <br> \u0db1\u0dd4\u0dc0\u0db1\u0dca \u0db4\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0daf\u0dd3\u0db4\u0dca \n|               image =\n|             country = Sri Lanka\n|            fullname = Aththachchi Nuwan Pradeep Roshan Fernando\n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|10|19|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Negombo]], [[Sri Lanka]]\n|            nickname = Siraa                                  \n|            heightft = 5                                         \n|          heightinch = 10                                                        \n|             heightm = 1.78                                                         \n|             batting = Right-hand batsman\n|             bowling = Right-arm [[Seam bowling|fast]]\n|              family = Nilakshi Champika (wife) (m.2015)\n|                role = [[Bowler (cricket)|Bowler]]\n|       international = true\n|       internationalspan = 2011\u2013present\n\n|       testdebutdate = 18 October\n|       testdebutyear = 2011\n|    testdebutagainst = Pakistan\n|             testcap = 119\n|        lasttestdate = 6 October\n|        lasttestyear = 2017\n|     lasttestagainst = Pakistan\n\n|        odidebutdate = 31 July\n|        odidebutyear = 2012\n|     odidebutagainst = India\n|              odicap = 153\n|         lastodidate = 1 March\n|         lastodiyear = 2020\n|      lastodiagainst = West Indies\n|            odishirt = 63\n\n|   T20Idebutagainst = England\n|      T20Idebutdate = 5 July\n|      T20Idebutyear = 2016\n|            T20Icap = 65\n|       lastT20Idate = 1 November\n|       lastT20Iyear = 2019\n|    lastT20Iagainst = Australia\n\n|               club1 = [[Burgher Recreation Club]]\n|               year1 = 2007\u201308\n|               club2 = [[Bloomfield Cricket and Athletic Club]]\n|               year2 = 2008\u20